{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QRcMfVmhVbonc951wVMqDL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock, one ladle at a time, until the rice is\n     2→creamy but still al dente, about 18-20 minutes. The risotto should flow slightly on the plate.\n     3→Season with salt and white pepper. Finish with butter and grated Parmigiano-Reggiano.\n     4→\n     5→CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA\n     6→\n     7→Slice the swordfish paper-thin. Arrange on chilled plates. Dress with extra virgin olive oil,\n     8→lemon juice, and sea salt. Scatter thinly shaved fennel and microgreens. Serve immediately.\n     9→\n    10→Preparation: 10 minutes\n    11→Serves: 4\n    12→\n    13→CARPACCIO WITH CITRUS DRESSING\n    14→\n    15→Place thin slices on a cold plate. Whisk together lemon, lime, orange juice with good quality\n    16→oil. Season with fıne sea salt and crushed coriander seeds. Garnish with fresh herbs and\n    17→thinly sliced radish.\n    18→\n    19→nto a loured work counter and knead until smooth, approx 8 minutes. Proof in oiled bowl, cover\n    20→with damp cloth, 45 minutes at room temperature. Shape into ½ dozen rounds. Second proof 30 min.\n    21→\n    22→Place pans in 225°C/435-VI0.. oven for 12-15 minutes until golden brown. Cool on wire rack.\n    23→\n    24→Makes: 1 dozen\n    25→\n    26→FRESH PASTA DOUGH\n    27→\n    28→125 grams plain flour\n    29→½ cup plus ı tablespoon water\n    30→Pinch of sea salt"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015NC4qY23ghoCGyD62h8XkS","session_id":"52c225dd-138d-420c-8852-ee28a481d2ae","uuid":"423bd585-7a68-4b1e-a9d2-6d4b3b8d8278"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GRFXQevWJnvs41SD6qhTWx","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 19 → 20: Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→1 failure out of 11 real-file test cases (90.9% pass rate). This is a **regression** — `Smażona zielona fasolka` passed in iteration 18 but fails in iteration 19. The root cause is that the `commonShort2` expansion (added to fix Pattern 2 from iter 18) collaterally admits Polish body-text lines as candidates. The multi-title guard then fails to reduce the result to a single title.\n     6→\n     7→This plan proposes 3 changes — two targeted fixes and one structural improvement — that together eliminate the regression while hardening against the broader class of \"body text leaking into candidates\" failures.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Root Cause Analysis\n    12→\n    13→### Why the regression happened\n    14→\n    15→Iteration 19 added Polish prepositions (`na`, `po`, `za`, `od`, etc.) to `commonShort2` to fix titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną`. This was correct — those titles were being garble-filtered. But the same short words appear frequently in Polish cooking instructions:\n    16→\n    17→- `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` (line 24, \"Serve hot or cold\") — `na` now passes\n    18→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` (line 22) — `na` now passes\n    19→\n    20→Both lines enter the candidate pool. The bilingual detection correctly suppresses `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` (the ALL_CAPS translation). But these body-text lines aren't translations — they're cooking instructions in Polish. No existing filter catches them.\n    21→\n    22→### Why the multi-title guard doesn't help\n    23→\n    24→After threshold filtering, `selected` contains `Smażona zielona fasolka` plus one or more body-text candidates. The multi-title guard checks `allCapsSelected`:\n    25→\n    26→```\n    27→allCapsSelected = selected.filter(s => isAllCaps(s.text)) → empty\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→When `allCapsSelected.length === 0`, the guard's implicit path is: **keep all candidates**. Both the title and the body-text line survive dedup (neither is a substring of the other). Result: `\"Smażona zielona fasolka + Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"`.\n    31→\n    32→### The fundamental gap\n    33→\n    34→The current pipeline has strong filters for:\n    35→- English cooking instructions (via `looksLikeCookingInstruction`)\n    36→- Garbled OCR text (via `isLikelyGarbled`)\n    37→- Ingredients, metadata, section labels\n    38→\n    39→But it has **no filter for Polish cooking instructions**. The English cooking-instruction filter (`COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS`) only recognizes English imperative verbs. Polish imperative verbs (`Podawaj`, `Dodaj`, `Smaż`, `Gotuj`) are invisible to it.\n    40→\n    41→Additionally, the multi-title guard's zero-ALL_CAPS path is a **no-op** — it keeps everything. This is a latent bug: in a single-recipe page with no ALL_CAPS titles, any mixed-case body text that passes filters will be returned alongside the real title.\n    42→\n    43→---\n    44→\n    45→## Change 1: Extend `looksLikeCookingInstruction` to Polish Imperative Verbs\n    46→\n    47→### What\n    48→\n    49→Add a parallel regex for Polish cooking verbs to the `looksLikeCookingInstruction` function.\n    50→\n    51→### Why\n    52→\n    53→The English cooking-instruction filter was added in iter 19 (Change 5 from the iter 18 plan) and works well for English garbage prologues. The same principle applies to Polish cooking instructions: they start with imperative verbs and are multi-word sentences. No recipe title starts with `Podawaj` (serve), `Dodaj` (add), `Smaż` (fry), or `Gotuj` (cook) followed by 3+ more words.\n    54→\n    55→### Proposed Change\n    56→\n    57→**Before:**\n    58→```typescript\n    59→const COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(beat|fold|stir|mix|add|pour|bake|cook|cool|remove|place|combine|whisk|knead|roll|spread|brush|slice|chop|dice|mince|drain|rinse|peel|grate|melt|simmer|boil|fry|sauté|saute|roast|grill|broil|steam|let|set|transfer|serve|garnish|arrange|sprinkle|season|preheat|cover|uncover|reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form)\\b/i;\n    60→\n    61→function looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n    62→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    63→  if (words.length < 4) return false;\n    64→  return COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim());\n    65→}\n    66→```\n    67→\n    68→**After:**\n    69→```typescript\n    70→const COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(beat|fold|stir|mix|add|pour|bake|cook|cool|remove|place|combine|whisk|knead|roll|spread|brush|slice|chop|dice|mince|drain|rinse|peel|grate|melt|simmer|boil|fry|sauté|saute|roast|grill|broil|steam|let|set|transfer|serve|garnish|arrange|sprinkle|season|preheat|cover|uncover|reduce|bring|toss|cut|trim|shape|form)\\b/i;\n    71→\n    72→// Polish imperative cooking verbs (with OCR-resilient forms — no diacritics required).\n    73→// These cover the most common recipe instruction starters. Includes common OCR-corrupted\n    74→// forms (e.g., \"Smaż\" → \"Smaz\", \"Dodaj\" → \"Dodaj\").\n    75→// Note: only verbs that NEVER start a recipe title. \"Piecz\" (bake) is excluded because\n    76→// \"Pieczeń\" (roast) and \"Pieczarki\" (mushrooms) share the prefix.\n    77→const POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS = /^(podawaj|dodaj|dodawaj|sma[zż]|gotuj|odced[zź]|wymiesza[jJ]|miesza[jJ]|wlej|nalej|przygotuj|zagotuj|pokr[oó]j|obierz|wrzuc|wrzuć|usma[zż]|podsma[zż]|prze[lł][oó][zż]|zblenduj|ubij|roztrzepaj|rozprowad[zź]|wyrob|zamieszaj|posyp|polej|odstaw|na[lł][oó][zż]|przykryj|odkryj|wstaw|zdejmij|ods[aą]cz|rozgrzej|posiekaj|zetrzyj|wy[lł][oó][zż]|wyjmij|ukr[oó]j|przekr[oó]j|formuj|ugniataj|rozwałkuj)\\b/i;\n    78→\n    79→function looksLikeCookingInstruction(text: string): boolean {\n    80→  const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n    81→  if (words.length < 4) return false;\n    82→  if (COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n    83→  if (POLISH_COOKING_INSTRUCTION_STARTS.test(text.trim())) return true;\n    84→  return false;\n    85→}\n    86→```\n    87→\n    88→### Directly affected lines in the failing file\n    89→\n    90→- `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` — starts with `Podawaj`, 6 words → **filtered**\n    91→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` — starts with `No`, not a verb → **not filtered by this change** (handled by Change 2 instead)\n    92→\n    93→### Risk assessment\n    94→\n    95→**Low risk.** The same principle as the English filter: imperative cooking verbs followed by 4+ words are never recipe titles. Polish recipe titles use nouns, adjectives, or past participles (`Smażona` = \"fried\", adjective), not imperative forms (`Smaż` = \"fry!\", imperative).\n    96→\n    97→Edge cases verified:\n    98→- `Smażona zielona fasolka` — starts with `Smażona` (adjective), not `Smaż` (imperative) → **safe**\n    99→- `Gotowane pierogi` — starts with `Gotowane` (past participle), not `Gotuj` → **safe**\n   100→- `Dodatkowe sosy` — starts with `Dodatkowe` (adjective), not `Dodaj` → **safe**\n   101→\n   102→### Expected impact\n   103→\n   104→Directly filters `Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno` and similar Polish instruction lines. Prevents this class of false positives across all files with Polish body text.\n   105→\n   106→---\n   107→\n   108→## Change 2: Position-Based Tiebreak for Zero-ALL_CAPS Multi-Candidate Results\n   109→\n   110→### What\n   111→\n   112→When the multi-title guard encounters multiple surviving candidates and **none** are ALL_CAPS, prefer the earliest candidate (lowest position) rather than keeping all.\n   113→\n   114→### Why\n   115→\n   116→The zero-ALL_CAPS path in the multi-title guard currently keeps all candidates:\n   117→\n   118→```typescript\n   119→if (selected.length > 1) {\n   120→  const allCapsSelected = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   121→  if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   122→    // ... multi-recipe page logic\n   123→  } else if (allCapsSelected.length === 1) {\n   124→    // ... single ALL_CAPS logic\n   125→  }\n   126→  // allCapsSelected.length === 0 → implicit: keep all ← THE BUG\n   127→}\n   128→```\n   129→\n   130→This implicit \"keep all\" is wrong for single-recipe pages. On a single-recipe page with a mixed-case title, any body-text line that leaks through filters becomes a second \"title\". The title is almost always the earliest candidate (position 0 or near it). Body-text lines appear later in the document.\n   131→\n   132→A true multi-title page with zero ALL_CAPS candidates (two mixed-case recipe titles on one page) is extremely rare in this corpus. And even in that case, returning just the first title is an acceptable degradation.\n   133→\n   134→### Proposed Change\n   135→\n   136→**Before (implicit):**\n   137→```typescript\n   138→// When allCapsSelected.length === 0: no action, keep all selected\n   139→```\n   140→\n   141→**After:**\n   142→```typescript\n   143→} else {\n   144→  // Zero ALL_CAPS survivors → single mixed-case recipe page.\n   145→  // No structural signal for multi-recipe detection. Use positional tiebreak:\n   146→  // the title is almost always the earliest candidate.\n   147→  // Score-based tiebreak within a position tolerance: if two candidates are within\n   148→  // 3 positions of each other, prefer the higher-scoring one.\n   149→  selected.sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   150→  const earliest = selected[0];\n   151→  const closeCompetitors = selected.filter(\n   152→    (s) => s.position <= earliest.position + 3 && s.score > earliest.score\n   153→  );\n   154→  selected = closeCompetitors.length > 0\n   155→    ? [closeCompetitors.reduce((a, b) => a.score > b.score ? a : b)]\n   156→    : [earliest];\n   157→}\n   158→```\n   159→\n   160→### Why a position tolerance\n   161→\n   162→Sometimes the title is at position 1 or 2 (after a blank line or a garbled fragment that was filtered). A rigid \"always pick position 0\" would miss these cases. The tolerance of 3 positions allows the algorithm to pick a higher-scoring candidate that's very close to position 0, while still strongly preferring early candidates over body-text lines at positions 20+.\n   163→\n   164→### Trace through the failing file\n   165→\n   166→```\n   167→Candidates after threshold: [\n   168→  \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" (position 0, score ~0.25),\n   169→  \"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\" (position 23, score ~0.12),  ← if Change 1 doesn't catch it\n   170→  (possibly other body-text lines)\n   171→]\n   172→allCapsSelected = [] → zero ALL_CAPS path\n   173→earliest = \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" (position 0)\n   174→closeCompetitors within 3 positions with higher score = none\n   175→selected = [\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"] ✓\n   176→```\n   177→\n   178→Even if Change 1 misses a particular body-text line (e.g., one that doesn't start with a known verb), Change 2 catches it by position.\n   179→\n   180→### Risk assessment\n   181→\n   182→**Low risk.** The only scenario where this could regress is a genuine multi-recipe page with zero ALL_CAPS titles. In the current corpus:\n   183→- All multi-recipe pages use ALL_CAPS titles (handled by the `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` branch)\n   184→- No test file has two mixed-case recipe titles on one page\n   185→- If such a file appears in the future, the fix is to handle it in the `allCapsSelected >= 2` branch (which already has multi-recipe logic), not in the zero-ALL_CAPS path\n   186→\n   187→### Expected impact\n   188→\n   189→Eliminates the regression in `Smażona zielona fasolka`. Also prevents any future regression where body-text lines leak into the zero-ALL_CAPS path.\n   190→\n   191→---\n   192→\n   193→## Change 3: Long-Line Body-Text Filter Based on Word Count\n   194→\n   195→### What\n   196→\n   197→Add a filter in `passesHardFilters` that rejects candidates with high word counts (≥8 words) that don't look like multi-part titles.\n   198→\n   199→### Why\n   200→\n   201→Recipe titles rarely exceed 7 words. Lines with 8+ words are almost always cooking instructions, ingredient descriptions, or body text. The line `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` has 12 words — no recipe title is that long.\n   202→\n   203→Currently there's a max *character* length (80 chars) but no max *word* count. A 12-word line at 65 characters passes the character limit.\n   204→\n   205→### Proposed Change\n   206→\n   207→Add to `passesHardFilters`, after the existing length check:\n   208→\n   209→```typescript\n   210→// Lines with ≥8 words are almost certainly body text, not titles.\n   211→// Exception: multi-title compounds with \" + \" or \" : \" separators are allowed\n   212→// (they're structurally distinct from continuous prose).\n   213→const words = text.trim().split(/\\s+/);\n   214→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:] /.test(text)) return false;\n   215→```\n   216→\n   217→### Directly affected lines in the failing file\n   218→\n   219→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` — 12 words → **filtered**\n   220→- `\"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno\"` — 6 words → **not filtered** (caught by Change 1 instead)\n   221→- `\"Smażona zielona fasolka\"` — 3 words → **safe**\n   222→\n   223→### Risk assessment\n   224→\n   225→**Very low risk.** Checked against all passing test expectations:\n   226→- Longest passing title: `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` — 9 \"words\" but contains ` : ` separator → exception applies\n   227→- `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` — 8 words, but actually 7 without the comma-separated part... let me check. The words split: `[\"Baked\", \"Eggs\", \"with\", \"Feta,\", \"Harissa\", \"Tomato\", \"Sauce\", \"&\", \"Coriander\"]` = 9 words. However, this contains no ` + ` or ` : ` separator. **This would be falsely filtered.**\n   228→\n   229→**Revised threshold:** Use 10 words instead of 8 to accommodate long legitimate titles:\n   230→\n   231→```typescript\n   232→if (words.length >= 10 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n   233→```\n   234→\n   235→Re-check:\n   236→- `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` — 9 words, contains ` & ` → exception applies → **safe**\n   237→- `\"HERB BAKED SALMON + DILL SAUCE VARIATION\"` — 6 words → **safe**\n   238→- `\"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\"` — 12 words, no separator → **filtered**\n   239→\n   240→Alternatively, if we want a tighter bound, use 8 words with the `&` exception:\n   241→\n   242→```typescript\n   243→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n   244→```\n   245→\n   246→- `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` — contains ` & ` → **safe**\n   247→- `\"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"` — contains ` + ` → **safe**\n   248→\n   249→This is the safer option. Use 8 words with the `+`, `:`, and `&` separator exception.\n   250→\n   251→### Expected impact\n   252→\n   253→Filters long body-text lines (12+ words) that slip through other checks. Acts as a safety net for the class of failures where body text lines are too long to be titles but don't start with known cooking verbs.\n   254→\n   255→---\n   256→\n   257→## Interaction Between Changes\n   258→\n   259→The three changes form defense-in-depth layers:\n   260→\n   261→1. **Change 1 (Polish cooking verbs):** Catches the specific `Podawaj...` line that caused this regression. Language-specific, precise.\n   262→\n   263→2. **Change 2 (position tiebreak):** Catches ANY body-text line that leaks through filters, regardless of language. Structural, general-purpose.\n   264→\n   265→3. **Change 3 (word count filter):** Catches very long lines (12-word cooking instructions) that don't start with known verbs. Language-agnostic, simple.\n   266→\n   267→For the specific failing file:\n   268→- Line 22 (`No potelni...`, 12 words): caught by Change 3\n   269→- Line 24 (`Podawaj no gorqco...`, 6 words): caught by Change 1\n   270→- If either line somehow survives both filters: caught by Change 2 (position tiebreak)\n   271→\n   272→Even if only ONE of the three changes is applied, the regression is fixed. All three together provide resilience against future variants.\n   273→\n   274→---\n   275→\n   276→## Implementation Order\n   277→\n   278→1. **Change 2 (position tiebreak)** — most general, fixes the regression regardless of what else is done. Zero risk of breaking other tests. Implement first.\n   279→2. **Change 1 (Polish cooking verbs)** — precise, addresses the root cause at the filter level. Improves candidate quality for all Polish-text files.\n   280→3. **Change 3 (word count filter)** — safety net. Apply last, verify against full corpus.\n   281→\n   282→---\n   283→\n   284→## Expected Impact\n   285→\n   286→| Change | Files Fixed | Risk | Complexity |\n   287→|--------|-------------|------|------------|\n   288→| 1. Polish cooking verbs | 1 (Smażona zielona fasolka) + future Polish files | Low | Low |\n   289→| 2. Position tiebreak | 1 (same) + general hardening | Very low | Low |\n   290→| 3. Word count filter | 1 (same) + general hardening | Very low | Trivial |\n   291→\n   292→**Expected pass rate after changes: 11/11 (100%) on real files.**\n   293→\n   294→All three changes are mutually reinforcing. Any single change fixes the current regression. Together, they close the broader gap that made the regression possible.\n   295→\n   296→---\n   297→\n   298→## Not Addressed (Accepted)\n   299→\n   300→### The `commonShort2` dual-purpose tension\n   301→\n   302→The feedback correctly identifies that `commonShort2` serves a dual purpose: whitelisting short words for title candidates AND inadvertently whitelisting them in body text. We do NOT propose reverting the `commonShort2` expansion — it's still needed for titles like `Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną`. Instead, we address the collateral effect through better downstream filtering (Changes 1–3).\n   303→\n   304→### OCR character substitution and missing words\n   305→\n   306→These remain accepted limitations (as noted in iter 18 plan). They require OCR-level fixes, not title-extraction logic.\n   307→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pyo1crR1vvt8EQ32wvXgRM","session_id":"52c225dd-138d-420c-8852-ee28a481d2ae","uuid":"2d36043b-c84e-44a6-ba86-5c297bcb3484"}
