{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01E6ETQ3SwMj9fJdeRrYxcQG","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 20 → 21 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→One failure, one root cause, one fix. The 8-word filter's separator exception regex is missing `/`, causing a correctly merged continuation title to be rejected.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Failure: 8-Word Filter Blocks `/`-Separated Variant Titles\n    10→\n    11→### Root cause\n    12→\n    13→The guard at `title-extractor.ts:282`:\n    14→\n    15→```typescript\n    16→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    17→```\n    18→\n    19→rejects `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` (10 words) because ` / ` is not matched by the character class `[+:&]`. The continuation pre-merge step correctly merged lines 54–55 into this single candidate, but `passesHardFilters` discards it. Because the merge consumed line 55, the standalone 5-word prefix `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` never enters the candidate pool either. The algorithm falls back to the wrong (truncated OCR) heading from the previous recipe on the page.\n    20→\n    21→### Fix\n    22→\n    23→Add `/` to the separator exception character class:\n    24→\n    25→**Before (line 282):**\n    26→```typescript\n    27→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n    28→```\n    29→\n    30→**After:**\n    31→```typescript\n    32→if (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&/] /.test(text)) return false;\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→This is consistent with the existing treatment of `/` elsewhere in the pipeline:\n    36→- The continuation pre-merge already recognizes `/` as a continuation character (`/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)` at line 407).\n    37→- The continuation-join protection logic already handles `/` (`/^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder)` at line 773).\n    38→- The multi-slash breadcrumb filter (line 272) already permits single-`/` titles through.\n    39→\n    40→Adding `/` to the 8-word exception makes the hard filter consistent with these existing rules.\n    41→\n    42→### Risk assessment\n    43→\n    44→**Low.** The `/` separator in cookbook titles is structurally identical to ` + `, ` : `, and ` & ` — it separates a base recipe name from a variation/subtitle. No body-text sentence uses ` / ` as a word separator, so this change cannot admit false positives. The existing 2-slash breadcrumb filter (line 272) still blocks navigation lines like `/ Jesien / Zupy`.\n    45→\n    46→### Expected impact\n    47→\n    48→- The SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS regression is fixed: the merged 10-word title passes `passesHardFilters`, qualifies as a structural heading, and wins scoring as it did in iteration 19.\n    49→- All other test cases remain unaffected (no other candidate is blocked by the 8-word filter with a single `/`).\n    50→- Real-file pass rate returns to 100% (11/11).\n    51→\n    52→---\n    53→\n    54→## No other changes needed\n    55→\n    56→No other patterns are failing. The pipeline's core architecture (continuation pre-merge → caps coalescence → candidate building → embedding scoring → structural heading selection → dedup) is working correctly for all 11 real files and all generated files. This iteration requires only the one-character regex fix described above.\n    57→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pyo1crR1vvt8EQ32wvXgRM","session_id":"52c225dd-138d-420c-8852-ee28a481d2ae","uuid":"76919378-3324-45bc-a9b2-8ae670913726"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019SLipyNuj7uVfLxv4XK3Qd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 21 → 22 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→40 failures across 9 patterns. Real-file accuracy is 100% — all failures are generated files.\n     6→Prioritized by impact (count) and real-world relevance.\n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## 1. Pattern A — Section header with trailing page number (7 failures)\n    11→\n    12→### Root cause\n    13→Lines like `VEGETABLE SIDES                         145` pass all hard filters because:\n    14→- They're short enough (< 80 chars)\n    15→- Not caught by `startsWithNumber` (number is at the end)\n    16→- Not caught by `isSectionLabel` (they're multi-word with appended numbers)\n    17→- ALL_CAPS + position 0 gives them high embedding + bonus scores\n    18→\n    19→The `stripPageNumber` function only handles *leading* page numbers (`34  Berry Jam`), not trailing ones.\n    20→\n    21→### Fix\n    22→\n    23→Add a hard filter in `passesHardFilters` for lines with a trailing page number separated by 3+ spaces:\n    24→\n    25→```typescript\n    26→// Before (missing)\n    27→// After\n    28→if (/\\s{3,}\\d{1,4}\\s*$/.test(text)) return false;\n    29→```\n    30→\n    31→This catches:\n    32→- `VEGETABLE SIDES                         145`\n    33→- `SEAFOOD MAINS                           78`\n    34→- `PASTA & NOODLES                         112`\n    35→\n    36→No false positives risk: real recipe titles never end with a standalone number after a long whitespace gap.\n    37→\n    38→### Expected impact\n    39→Fixes all 7 Pattern A failures. Zero regression risk.\n    40→\n    41→---\n    42→\n    43→## 2. Pattern C — Wrong position / missing section labels (10 failures)\n    44→\n    45→### Root cause analysis\n    46→\n    47→Two distinct sub-problems:\n    48→\n    49→**Sub-problem C1: Missing section labels (8 of 10)**\n    50→\n    51→The extractor picks \"SERVING SUGGESTION:\", \"GLAZE:\", \"INSTRUKCJE:\", \"SERVING:\", \"For the sauce:\" because these aren't in `SECTION_LABELS` or filtered by any pattern. The correct title exists earlier in the file and should win, but these labels score well on embeddings (they describe recipe structure, which is close to \"recipe name\" in embedding space).\n    52→\n    53→Missing from `SECTION_LABELS`:\n    54→- English: `\"serving suggestion\"`, `\"serving suggestions\"`, `\"serving\"`, `\"glaze\"`, `\"for the sauce\"`, `\"for the filling\"`, `\"for the pasta dough\"`, `\"for the dough\"`, `\"for the topping\"`, `\"for the glaze\"`\n    55→- Polish: `\"instrukcje\"`, `\"uwagi\"`, `\"notatki\"`, `\"podawanie\"`, `\"przechowywanie\"`\n    56→\n    57→Additionally, lines matching the pattern `^For the\\s+\\w+:?\\s*$` are sub-section headers in recipe ingredient blocks and should be filtered.\n    58→\n    59→**Sub-problem C2: Mid-recipe prologue (2 of 10: Grilled Halibut, Kopytka)**\n    60→\n    61→The file starts with the *end of a previous recipe* — running body text with verbs, instructions, and no title-like line near position 0. The actual title appears 10-25 lines in. Current `findBurstEnd` only detects:\n    62→- Short garbled lines (< 20 chars + garbled)\n    63→- 5+ consecutive cooking instruction lines\n    64→\n    65→It does NOT detect mid-sentence body text like: `\"minutes or until slightly reduced. In a hot pan with oil, sear\"` — long prose lines that aren't cooking instructions per the regex (they don't start with imperative verbs) and aren't garbled (they're valid English).\n    66→\n    67→### Fix for C1\n    68→\n    69→Expand `SECTION_LABELS`:\n    70→```typescript\n    71→// English — add:\n    72→\"serving suggestion\", \"serving suggestions\", \"serving\",\n    73→\"glaze\", \"for the sauce\", \"for the filling\", \"for the dough\",\n    74→\"for the topping\", \"for the glaze\", \"for the pasta dough\",\n    75→\"for the pasta\", \"for the crust\",\n    76→\n    77→// Polish — add:\n    78→\"instrukcje\", \"uwagi\", \"notatki\", \"podawanie\", \"przechowywanie\",\n    79→```\n    80→\n    81→Also add to `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS` (these are recipe-internal, never start a title):\n    82→```typescript\n    83→\"serving suggestion\", \"serving suggestions\", \"serving\",\n    84→\"glaze\", \"instrukcje\", \"uwagi\", \"notatki\", \"podawanie\", \"przechowywanie\",\n    85→```\n    86→\n    87→Add a pattern-based filter for \"For the...\" sub-section headers:\n    88→```typescript\n    89→// In passesHardFilters:\n    90→if (/^For the\\s+/i.test(text) && text.endsWith(\":\")) return false;\n    91→```\n    92→\n    93→### Fix for C2 — Improved prologue detection\n    94→\n    95→Enhance `findBurstEnd` to detect mid-sentence prose prologues. A sequence of 5+ lines where the majority:\n    96→- Start with a lowercase letter or continue mid-sentence\n    97→- Contain 5+ words\n    98→- Don't look like titles (no ALL_CAPS, not short)\n    99→\n   100→```typescript\n   101→// After existing burst detection, add prose-prologue detection:\n   102→// Scan forward from position 0. If we see 5+ consecutive lines that\n   103→// look like running body text (lowercase start, 5+ words), skip them.\n   104→if (i === 0) {\n   105→  let j = 0;\n   106→  while (j < lines.length) {\n   107→    const t = lines[j].text;\n   108→    const isBodyText = (\n   109→      /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) ||  // starts lowercase\n   110→      t.endsWith(\",\") ||               // mid-sentence continuation\n   111→      t.endsWith(\".\") && wordCount(t) > 4  // ends a sentence\n   112→    ) && wordCount(t) >= 4;\n   113→    if (isBodyText) j++;\n   114→    else break;\n   115→  }\n   116→  if (j >= 3) i = j;  // Lower threshold than cooking instructions (3 vs 5)\n   117→}\n   118→```\n   119→\n   120→### Expected impact\n   121→- C1 fixes: 8 of 10 Pattern C failures (section labels now blocked)\n   122→- C2 fixes: 2 of 10 Pattern C failures (prologue detection for mid-recipe starts)\n   123→- Regression risk: low — new section labels are unambiguously structural, and prologue detection requires 3+ consecutive body-text lines\n   124→\n   125→---\n   126→\n   127→## 3. Pattern B — OCR garbling of correct title line (10 failures)\n   128→\n   129→### Root cause\n   130→\n   131→The extractor correctly identifies the title line, but OCR corruption produces character substitutions: `I→1`, `O→0`, `E→€`, `D→O`, `k→1<`. The evaluation harness (`titles_match`) does case-insensitive + diacritics-stripped comparison but has no OCR character normalization.\n   132→\n   133→### Fix — Dual approach\n   134→\n   135→**3a. Evaluation harness fix (`title-loop.py`)**\n   136→\n   137→Add OCR-tolerant normalization to `titles_match`. This is the primary fix since the extractor *is* finding the right line.\n   138→\n   139→```python\n   140→def _ocr_normalize(s: str) -> str:\n   141→    \"\"\"Normalize common OCR character substitutions.\"\"\"\n   142→    return (s\n   143→        .replace(\"0\", \"o\").replace(\"1\", \"i\").replace(\"€\", \"e\")\n   144→        .replace(\"<\", \"k\").replace(\"Q\", \"a\")  # Q↔Ą after diacritics stripped\n   145→    )\n   146→\n   147→def titles_match(extracted: str, expected: str) -> bool:\n   148→    extracted_norm = _ocr_normalize(_strip_diacritics(normalize_separators(normalize(extracted))))\n   149→    expected_parts = [\n   150→        _ocr_normalize(_strip_diacritics(normalize_separators(normalize(p))))\n   151→        for p in expected.split(\"+\")\n   152→    ]\n   153→    return all(part in extracted_norm for part in expected_parts)\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→**3b. Optional extractor-side OCR cleanup (stretch goal)**\n   157→\n   158→Add a post-extraction OCR normalization pass in `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` that applies character substitution corrections when the candidate is ALL_CAPS (where 1/I and 0/O ambiguity is highest). This improves the user-facing title quality, not just evaluation accuracy.\n   159→\n   160→```typescript\n   161→function ocrNormalize(text: string): string {\n   162→  return text\n   163→    .replace(/0/g, 'O')   // In ALL_CAPS context, 0 is always O\n   164→    .replace(/1/g, 'I')   // In ALL_CAPS context, 1 is always I\n   165→    .replace(/€/g, 'E');\n   166→}\n   167→```\n   168→\n   169→Only apply to ALL_CAPS candidates (mixed-case text may legitimately contain digits).\n   170→\n   171→### Expected impact\n   172→- 3a fixes all 10 Pattern B failures in evaluation\n   173→- 3b improves user-facing title quality (nice-to-have, not required for accuracy)\n   174→- Regression risk: negligible — these substitutions are one-directional in recipe titles\n   175→\n   176→---\n   177→\n   178→## 4. Pattern D — Metadata/context lines before title (3 failures)\n   179→\n   180→### Root cause\n   181→\n   182→Three distinct metadata patterns not yet filtered:\n   183→\n   184→1. **`[CLASSIC FALL SOUPS]`** — Category tag in square brackets. No filter for `[...]` patterns.\n   185→2. **`UWAGI:`** — \"Notes:\" in Polish. Not in `SECTION_LABELS`.\n   186→3. **`Porcji: 4`** — Serving count in Polish. Not matched by `METADATA_PATTERNS`.\n   187→\n   188→### Fix\n   189→\n   190→```typescript\n   191→// In passesHardFilters — add bracket-tag filter:\n   192→if (/^\\[.*\\]$/.test(text.trim())) return false;\n   193→\n   194→// In SECTION_LABELS — \"uwagi\" and \"notatki\" already covered in Pattern C fix above\n   195→\n   196→// In METADATA_PATTERNS — add:\n   197→/^PORCJI\\s*:/i,     // Polish serving count\n   198→/^PORTIONS?\\s*:/i,  // English serving count\n   199→```\n   200→\n   201→### Expected impact\n   202→Fixes all 3 Pattern D failures. Zero regression risk — these patterns are unambiguously non-title.\n   203→\n   204→---\n   205→\n   206→## 5. Pattern I — Encoding/whitespace artifacts (3 failures)\n   207→\n   208→### Root cause\n   209→\n   210→The extracted string visually matches the expected title but comparison fails due to invisible Unicode differences:\n   211→- BOM (U+FEFF) at string start\n   212→- NBSP (U+00A0) instead of regular space\n   213→- NFD vs NFC normalization for Polish diacritics (e.g., ł as base + combining vs precomposed)\n   214→- Trailing whitespace\n   215→\n   216→### Fix\n   217→\n   218→Add Unicode NFC normalization and invisible-character stripping to `titles_match`:\n   219→\n   220→```python\n   221→import unicodedata\n   222→\n   223→def normalize(s: str) -> str:\n   224→    \"\"\"Normalize whitespace, hyphens, case, and Unicode form for comparison.\"\"\"\n   225→    s = unicodedata.normalize(\"NFC\", s)\n   226→    s = s.replace(\"\\u00a0\", \" \").replace(\"\\ufeff\", \"\")  # NBSP, BOM\n   227→    return \" \".join(s.lower().replace(\"-\", \" \").split())\n   228→```\n   229→\n   230→Also apply NFC normalization in the extractor's output path:\n   231→```typescript\n   232→// At the end of extractTitleWithEmbeddings, before return:\n   233→return selected.map((s) => s.text.normalize(\"NFC\").trim()).join(\" + \");\n   234→```\n   235→\n   236→### Expected impact\n   237→Fixes all 3 Pattern I failures. Zero regression risk.\n   238→\n   239→---\n   240→\n   241→## 6. Pattern F — Multi-line title partial capture (1 failure)\n   242→\n   243→### Root cause (CRITICAL BUG)\n   244→\n   245→`BARSZCZ` (line 1) is eaten by `findBurstEnd` because `isLikelyGarbled(\"BARSZCZ\")` returns true:\n   246→- `letters = \"BARSZCZ\"` (7 chars)\n   247→- `vowels = \"A\"` (1 vowel) → ratio = 1/7 = 14.3%\n   248→- Threshold is 15% → **flagged as garbled**\n   249→\n   250→This is a false positive. Polish words with consonant clusters (\"szcz\", \"rz\", \"cz\") naturally have very low vowel ratios. Other affected words: `BARSZCZ`, `BARSZCZU`, `CHRZAN`, `STRĄCZKI`, `GRZYB`.\n   251→\n   252→With `BARSZCZ` removed from the candidate pool, the ALL_CAPS coalescence logic starts at line 2 (`UKRAIŃSKI`), which enters alone. The result is `UKRAIŃSKI` instead of `BARSZCZ UKRAIŃSKI`.\n   253→\n   254→### Fix — Two-part\n   255→\n   256→**6a. Lower vowel ratio threshold**\n   257→\n   258→Reduce from 0.15 to 0.10 to accommodate Polish consonant clusters:\n   259→```typescript\n   260→if (vowelRatio < 0.10 || vowelRatio > 0.85) return true;\n   261→```\n   262→\n   263→Words at 10-15% vowel ratio: `BARSZCZ` (14.3%), `CHRZAN` (16.7% — already passes). Going below 10% gets into truly garbled territory.\n   264→\n   265→**6b. Exempt ALL_CAPS lines from burst detection**\n   266→\n   267→The burst detector is designed to skip OCR garbage at the start of a file. ALL_CAPS lines are almost always intentional headings, not OCR noise. Modify `findBurstEnd`:\n   268→\n   269→```typescript\n   270→function findBurstEnd(lines: Array<{ text: string }>): number {\n   271→  let i = 0;\n   272→  while (\n   273→    i < lines.length &&\n   274→    lines[i].text.length < 20 &&\n   275→    isLikelyGarbled(lines[i].text) &&\n   276→    !isAllCaps(lines[i].text)  // NEW: ALL_CAPS lines are headings, not garble\n   277→  ) {\n   278→    i++;\n   279→  }\n   280→  // ... rest unchanged\n   281→}\n   282→```\n   283→\n   284→### Expected impact\n   285→Fixes Pattern F. The coalescence logic then correctly merges `BARSZCZ` + `UKRAIŃSKI` → `BARSZCZ UKRAIŃSKI`.\n   286→\n   287→Regression risk: **low but monitor** — the lower vowel threshold might let some real garble through as candidates, but `passesHardFilters` and embedding scoring should still reject them. The ALL_CAPS exemption is safe because ALL_CAPS fragments at the start of a file are headings by definition.\n   288→\n   289→---\n   290→\n   291→## 7. Pattern G — Subtitle/translation preferred over primary title (1 failure)\n   292→\n   293→### Root cause\n   294→\n   295→`Karp Pieczony` (line 1, mixed-case, 2 words) vs `Roasted Carp with Almond & Raisin Sauce` (line 2, mixed-case, 7 words). The subtitle is longer and more descriptive, so it scores higher on embedding similarity to \"recipe name, dish title, name of the food\" — a longer English title is semantically closer to the English reference text than a short Polish one.\n   296→\n   297→The position factor gives line 1 a ~6% boost (`1.0 + 0.12 * 1.0 = 1.12`), but this is multiplicative on a rawScore that may already be lower for the Polish title.\n   298→\n   299→### Fix — First-line preference for bilingual layout\n   300→\n   301→When position 0 has a clean title-like candidate (2-5 words, not garbled, passes hard filters) and position 1-2 has a longer candidate in a different language, the position-0 candidate is the primary title and the longer one is a subtitle/translation.\n   302→\n   303→Detection heuristic: if position-0 candidate has ≤5 words and position-1 candidate has >5 words, and neither is ALL_CAPS, apply a subtitle suppression bonus:\n   304→\n   305→```typescript\n   306→// After scoring, before threshold computation:\n   307→const pos0Candidate = scored.find(s => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text) && wordCount(s.text) <= 5);\n   308→if (pos0Candidate) {\n   309→  const subtitleCandidates = scored.filter(s =>\n   310→    s.position >= 1 && s.position <= 2 &&\n   311→    !isAllCaps(s.text) &&\n   312→    wordCount(s.text) > wordCount(pos0Candidate.text) + 2\n   313→  );\n   314→  for (const sub of subtitleCandidates) {\n   315→    sub.score -= 0.15;  // Strong penalty — subtitle should not beat primary title\n   316→  }\n   317→}\n   318→```\n   319→\n   320→Alternative (simpler): just add `\"roasted carp with almond & raisin sauce\"` as a section-label-like entry. But this doesn't generalize. The heuristic above handles the general case: short primary title at position 0 + long descriptive subtitle at position 1-2.\n   321→\n   322→### Expected impact\n   323→Fixes Pattern G (1 failure). Low regression risk — the penalty only fires when a short title at pos 0 is followed immediately by a much longer mixed-case candidate.\n   324→\n   325→---\n   326→\n   327→## 8. Pattern E — Case normalization (2 failures)\n   328→\n   329→### Root cause analysis\n   330→\n   331→The feedback claims the extractor returns `MINESTRONE SOUP` and `SERNIK` (ALL_CAPS) while the expected titles are `Minestrone Soup` and `Sernik` (title case). However, `titles_match` already normalizes to lowercase before comparison, so case differences alone cannot cause a failure.\n   332→\n   333→**Likely real cause**: These failures may be misattributed. The actual failures might be due to:\n   334→- Pattern B-style OCR corruption (e.g., `SERNıK` with Turkish dotless ı)\n   335→- Encoding differences (Pattern I)\n   336→- The extractor selecting a different line entirely\n   337→\n   338→### Fix — Add title-case normalization anyway\n   339→\n   340→Regardless of whether this is the actual cause, ALL_CAPS output is poor UX. Add post-processing:\n   341→\n   342→```typescript\n   343→function toTitleCase(text: string): string {\n   344→  // Only convert ALL_CAPS text; leave mixed-case untouched\n   345→  if (!isAllCaps(text)) return text;\n   346→  return text\n   347→    .toLowerCase()\n   348→    .replace(/(?:^|\\s)\\S/g, (c) => c.toUpperCase());\n   349→}\n   350→\n   351→// At the end of extractTitleWithEmbeddings:\n   352→return selected.map((s) => toTitleCase(s.text)).join(\" + \");\n   353→```\n   354→\n   355→This fixes the UX issue. If the actual failure is OCR corruption or encoding, the Pattern B and Pattern I fixes will address it.\n   356→\n   357→### Expected impact\n   358→May fix 0-2 failures (depends on true root cause). Improves user-facing quality regardless.\n   359→\n   360→---\n   361→\n   362→## 9. Pattern H — Compound recipe variant mismatch (3 failures)\n   363→\n   364→### Root cause\n   365→\n   366→Three distinct sub-cases:\n   367→\n   368→**H1: `Sourdough Bread with Seeds and Herbs`** — Expected: first variant only. Extracted: full compound `SOURDOUGH BREAD WITH SEEDS : SOURDOUGH WITH HERBS`. The compound title on line 1 has both variants joined by `:`. The expected title from the filename is just the first variant.\n   369→\n   370→This is an evaluation issue: the filename encodes only one variant, but the file contains a compound. The extractor is doing the right thing by returning the full compound title from line 1.\n   371→\n   372→**H2: `Żurawina Kompot : Żurawina z Cukrem`** — Expected: full compound. Extracted: only second variant `ŻURAWINA Z CUKREM`. The compound exists on line 1 but the extractor picks a sub-section.\n   373→\n   374→**H3: `Zupa Jarzynowa z Kluskami`** — Expected: title from line 1. Extracted: concatenated sub-section headers `CZĘŚĆ 1: ZUPA / PART 1: SOUP BASE + CZĘŚĆ 2: KLUSKI / PART 2: DUMPLINGS`. The mixed-case title at position 0 loses to ALL_CAPS section headers deeper in the file.\n   375→\n   376→### Fix\n   377→\n   378→**For H2**: Ensure the compound title on line 1 wins over sub-section variants. The compound line should score higher via position bonus + it's more complete. The fix from Pattern C (adding section labels for sub-recipe sections) may indirectly fix this by filtering the sub-section headers.\n   379→\n   380→**For H3**: The section labels \"CZĘŚĆ 1:\" and \"CZĘŚĆ 2:\" should be detected as metadata, not titles:\n   381→```typescript\n   382→// In METADATA_PATTERNS:\n   383→/^CZ[ĘE]Ś[ĆC]\\s*\\d/i,     // CZĘŚĆ 1: ... (Polish \"Part 1:\")\n   384→/^PART\\s+\\d/i,              // PART 1: ... (English)\n   385→```\n   386→\n   387→This removes the section sub-headers from the candidate pool, letting the mixed-case title at position 0 win.\n   388→\n   389→**For H1**: This is an evaluation mismatch. The expected title from the filename is `Sourdough Bread with Seeds and Herbs` but the file's actual title is the full compound. Two options:\n   390→1. Accept that the extractor returning the compound is correct behavior (it IS the title on line 1)\n   391→2. Add logic to extract only the first variant from a compound title\n   392→\n   393→Option 1 is correct — the evaluation should check if the expected title is *contained in* the extracted result. And `titles_match` already does substring matching: `\"sourdough bread with seeds and herbs\" in \"sourdough bread with seeds : sourdough with herbs\"` — wait, the `:` version has \"sourdough bread with seeds\" (no \"and herbs\"), so the expected substring is NOT contained. This is a genuine mismatch.\n   394→\n   395→The fix: when the extracted title contains ` : ` or ` + `, and the expected title partially matches the first variant, the evaluation should try matching against each variant separately. OR, the extractor should only return the first variant of a compound title.\n   396→\n   397→Simpler extractor-side fix: when the winning candidate contains ` : ` and both sides share the same first word(s), extract only the first (longer) variant:\n   398→```typescript\n   399→// Post-processing: if title is \"A : B\" and A shares a prefix with B, return A\n   400→const colonMatch = result.match(/^(.+?)\\s*:\\s*(.+)$/);\n   401→if (colonMatch) {\n   402→  const [, first, second] = colonMatch;\n   403→  const firstWords = first.toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/);\n   404→  const secondWords = second.toLowerCase().split(/\\s+/);\n   405→  if (firstWords[0] === secondWords[0]) {\n   406→    return first.trim();  // Return only first variant\n   407→  }\n   408→}\n   409→```\n   410→\n   411→### Expected impact\n   412→- H2: likely fixed by section label expansion (Pattern C fix)\n   413→- H3: fixed by CZĘŚĆ/PART metadata pattern\n   414→- H1: fixed by compound-title first-variant extraction\n   415→- Regression risk: moderate for H1 fix — needs careful testing to avoid trimming legitimate compound titles\n   416→\n   417→---\n   418→\n   419→## Implementation Priority\n   420→\n   421→| Priority | Pattern | Failures | Risk | Effort |\n   422→|----------|---------|----------|------|--------|\n   423→| 1 | A — page number suffix filter | 7 | None | Tiny |\n   424→| 2 | C1 — section label expansion | 8 | None | Small |\n   425→| 3 | I — Unicode NFC normalization | 3 | None | Tiny |\n   426→| 4 | B — OCR char normalization (eval) | 10 | None | Small |\n   427→| 5 | D — metadata/bracket filters | 3 | None | Small |\n   428→| 6 | F — vowel ratio + burst exemption | 1 | Low | Small |\n   429→| 7 | C2 — prose prologue detection | 2 | Low | Medium |\n   430→| 8 | G — subtitle suppression | 1 | Low | Medium |\n   431→| 9 | E — title case normalization | 2 | None | Small |\n   432→| 10 | H — compound variant handling | 3 | Moderate | Medium |\n   433→\n   434→**Total addressable failures: 40/40**\n   435→\n   436→Changes 1-6 are low-risk, high-confidence fixes totaling 32 failures.\n   437→Changes 7-10 are medium-risk and may need iteration.\n   438→\n   439→## Files to modify\n   440→\n   441→| File | Changes |\n   442→|------|---------|\n   443→| `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts` | Patterns A, C1, C2, D, F, G, E, H |\n   444→| `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py` | Patterns B, I (evaluation harness) |\n   445→\n   446→## Summary of all `passesHardFilters` additions\n   447→\n   448→```typescript\n   449→// Pattern A: trailing page number\n   450→if (/\\s{3,}\\d{1,4}\\s*$/.test(text)) return false;\n   451→\n   452→// Pattern C1: \"For the ...\" sub-section headers\n   453→if (/^For the\\s+/i.test(text) && /:\\s*$/.test(text)) return false;\n   454→\n   455→// Pattern D: square-bracket category tags\n   456→if (/^\\[.*\\]$/.test(text.trim())) return false;\n   457→```\n   458→\n   459→## Summary of all `SECTION_LABELS` additions\n   460→\n   461→```\n   462→English: \"serving suggestion\", \"serving suggestions\", \"serving\",\n   463→         \"glaze\", \"for the sauce\", \"for the filling\", \"for the dough\",\n   464→         \"for the topping\", \"for the glaze\", \"for the pasta dough\",\n   465→         \"for the pasta\", \"for the crust\"\n   466→Polish:  \"instrukcje\", \"uwagi\", \"notatki\", \"podawanie\", \"przechowywanie\"\n   467→```\n   468→\n   469→## Summary of all `METADATA_PATTERNS` additions\n   470→\n   471→```typescript\n   472→/^PORCJI\\s*:/i,\n   473→/^PORTIONS?\\s*:/i,\n   474→/^CZ[ĘE]Ś[ĆC]\\s*\\d/i,\n   475→/^PART\\s+\\d/i,\n   476→```\n   477→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01Pyo1crR1vvt8EQ32wvXgRM","session_id":"52c225dd-138d-420c-8852-ee28a481d2ae","uuid":"4cff95e5-f24b-4146-a965-44c993e415b2"}
