{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01EXMouuibGRk5izeo8rYQPQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase, the failure patterns, and the history. Let me think through the key changes needed and write the improvement plan.\n\nLet me think about each pattern:\n\n**Pattern 1: OCR digit/letter substitution (11 failures)**\nThe extractor correctly identifies the title line but returns OCR-corrupted text. Need a post-processing OCR normalization step. Key substitutions: `1→l/I`, `0→O`, `4→A`, `¡→i`, `€→E`. Also need to handle stray suffix like `+ SERVÍNG AND STORAGE:`.\n\n\n**Pattern 2: Section/category header or page reference chosen (6 failures)**\nI need to filter out page references like \"Page 42\" and \"Strona 65\" with regex patterns, and also catch generic food category headers like \"VEGETABLES\" or \"FISH & SEAFOOD\" that appear as section labels rather than recipe titles.\n**Pattern 3: Previous-page overflow (2 failures)**\nLines containing overflow markers from previous pages need to be excluded.\n**Pattern 4: Multi-part title truncated (4 failures)**\nThe compound title logic is incorrectly stripping shared first words—when I see \"LEMON CURD : LEMON CURD WITH THYME\", the code removes the duplicate \"LEMON\" prefix and returns just \"LEMON CURD\", but the expected output is the full compound title. I need to preserve the complete multi-part title instead of deduplicating it.\n\nThere are also cases where the extractor is pulling the wrong section entirely—picking variation headers or subsections from inside the recipe body instead of the actual title line, or only capturing one half of a compound title when both parts should be included. the main issue is the compound-variant stripping logic at lines 999-1009. It strips `:` compounds when both sides share first word, but the expected behavior is to keep the full compound. This logic was presumably added in an earlier iteration to solve a different problem. It needs to be removed or made conditional.\n\n**Pattern 5: Multi-line title not joined (4 failures)**\n- \"LEMON HERB RO45TED\" / \"VEGETABLES\" → extracted \"VEGETABLES\". The caps coalescing should join these, but \"RO45TED\" has digits so maybe `isAllCaps` fails?\n- \"PLACKI\" / \"ŻÓŁTE\" / \"Z KUKURYDZĄ\" → extracted \"ŻÓŁTE Z KUKURYDZĄ\". Missing the first line.\n- \"ROSEMARY\" / \"FOCACCIA\" / \"BREAD\" → extracted \"TOPPING & BAKING:\". The caps coalescing should handle three single-word lines, but something's preventing the title from being captured. I'm wondering if one of these words is accidentally in the section labels set, or if there's an issue with how the lines are being filtered before coalescing. I'm second-guessing myself on how the caps coalescing works. The file has ROSEMARY, FOCACCIA, and BREAD on separate lines with a blank line after, so they'd be merged into \"ROSEMARY FOCACCIA BREAD\" since each word meets the constraints. But the test is failing, so maybe the algorithm is taking a different path than I'm assuming. Let me trust the feedback and work on a fix.\n\nLooking at the actual failures, I notice \"TOPPING & BAKING:\" is being extracted instead of the merged title, which suggests `passesHardFilters` might be rejecting \"ROSEMARY FOCACCIA BREAD\" even though it's 3 words and 25 characters. For the hyphenated case like \"ROASTED CHICKEN WITH ROOT VEGET-\" / \"ABLES\", the caps coalescing won't merge them because the first part exceeds 25 characters and has 5 words, and the continuation merge won't fire since \"ABLES\" doesn't match the expected pattern. I need to add logic to handle hyphen-broken words specifically.\n\nNow looking at the OCR corruption pattern with \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\" — the title starts with uppercase but contains digit substitutions. I'm checking whether `isLikelyGarbled` would reject it by examining if words like \"w1th\" trigger the garbled detection, considering that \"w\" is lowercase with only 1 alpha character. commonShort2? \"w\" is in there. Wait no — the word is \"w1th\", not \"w\". `w.toLowerCase()` = \"w1th\". Is \"w1th\" in commonShort2? No. But `w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length` = 3 (\"wth\"). That's >2, so it doesn't match the garbled condition (which requires ≤2 alpha chars). So \"w1th\" wouldn't be caught by that filter.\n\nActually wait — `isLikelyGarbled` checks: `words.some((w) => /^[a-z]/.test(w) && w.replace(/[^a-z]/g, \"\").length <= 2 && !commonShort2.has(w.toLowerCase()))`. So for \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\": \"w1th\" starts with lowercase, replace non-alpha = \"wth\" length 3, so ≤2 fails. Let me trace through the full garbled check — the string has letters, vowel ratio is around 16% which passes the 10% threshold, it's multi-word so no single-word checks apply, and I need to verify the other conditions. with lowercase? \"Bra1sed\" starts with B (uppercase). No.\n6. Mid-text sentence boundary? No.\n7. Multi-word garbled check: for each word, check if starts with lowercase, has ≤2 alpha chars, and not in commonShort2. \"w1th\" — starts with lowercase ✓, alpha chars = \"wth\" = 3 chars ≤2? No. So it passes.\n\nSo \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\" should NOT be caught by isLikelyGarbled. But then why does it fail? The feedback says extracted is \"(empty)\" for this file. Let me think... Maybe `passesHardFilters` rejects it for another reason?\n\nLooking at passesHardFilters:\n- Length 3-80? \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\" = ~27 chars. Fine.\n- looksLikeIngredient? No measurement patterns. Fine.\n- startsWithNumber? No. Fine.\n- looksLikeMetadata? No. Fine.\n- isLikelyGarbled? Let me recalculate the vowel ratio more carefully. Extracting just the letters: \"BrasedCodwthWhteWne\" gives me 19 characters total. Counting vowels (a, e, i, o, u): a appears twice, o once, e twice, so 5 vowels total. That's a ratio of 5/19 ≈ 0.26, which is above the 0.2 threshold, so it shouldn't fail on vowel ratio either.\n\nWait, let me recount the vowels in \"BrasedCodwthWhteWne\" character by character: B-r-a-s-e-d-C-o-d-w-t-h-W-h-t-e-W-n-e. The vowels are: a (position 3), e (position 5), o (position 8), e (position 16), e (position 19). That's 5 vowels, ratio 5/19 ≈ 0.26. Still passes.\n\nHmm, but the regex includes y and Polish vowels too. Let me check if there's a y in there... no y. So 5 vowels is correct. This should pass the garble check.\n\nThen I'm checking against cooking instruction patterns — \"Bra1sed\" doesn't match any of the common cooking verbs like \"beat\" or \"fold\". It passes that filter too. Not all caps, not a section label. So it should pass all the hard filters, but somehow the result is empty. Maybe the issue is earlier in the processing, like on the first line?\n\nActually, I'm probably overcomplicating this. The real problem might be that the embedding similarity score for OCR-corrupted text drops below the threshold, filtering it out before it even gets to the output.\n\nFor the extraction failures, I'm seeing a pattern: single-word titles like \"Golonka\" and \"MAKOWIEC\" aren't getting the structural bonuses they need to compete with other candidates like \"Roasting:\" or \"PASTA MAKOWA:\". Even though \"MAKOWIEC\" is all caps, it's still just one word, which limits how much the scoring can boost it. —single-word titles, especially when they're all caps, tend to score lower than multi-word section headers. That's a real issue.\n\nFor \"Sweet Potato Salad,\" the title is buried at line 29, so the algorithm picks up \"Salt and pepper\" instead. The position bonus can't help when the actual title is that far down. I should probably return empty rather than noise when there's no title in the top portion.\n\nLooking at the overall strategy, the embeddings plus heuristics approach works well on real files, but these generated test cases are exposing edge cases that feel increasingly artificial. That said, some of these patterns—OCR normalization, skipping section headers, handling single-word titles, joining multi-line text—do show up in real-world scenarios.\n\nI'm thinking about a few key improvements. First, I should add OCR normalization as a post-processing step to handle patterns like \"0\" vs \"O\" and \"1\" vs \"l\".  The insight here is that I only need to normalize the output, not the input—the corrupted input actually helps find the right line. Then I can apply title case. For the normalization itself, I could use a heuristic: if the word is all caps, treat \"1\" as \"I\" and \"0\" as \"O\"; if it's mixed case, treat \"1\" as \"l\" instead.\n\nSecond, I need to strengthen the hard filters to catch page numbers and section headers like \"Page 1\" or similar patterns that shouldn't be considered titles.\n\nI should also extend the burst-end detection to skip lines containing words like \"PREVIOUS\", \"OVERFLOW\", or \"CONTINUATION\" that indicate content spilling over from another page.\n\nThe compound title stripping logic is too aggressive—it's removing legitimate titles like \"LEMON CURD : LEMON CURD WITH THYME\" when both sides share a word. I need to either remove or condition that logic.\n\nFinally, I'm looking at handling hyphen continuations where titles are split across lines.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":866,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5861,"cache_read_input_tokens":64554,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5861},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"52c225dd-138d-420c-8852-ee28a481d2ae","uuid":"b34c52b1-a410-43f8-977a-ae36c2fcbde1"}
